SWAT_CANCEL_SUMMARY:
This group planned to use 35 different instances of Weave for their single-location business, to allow for sales representatives to have different outbound caller ID numbers and texting numbers. They also planned to solely use the mobile app rather than physical or softphones.
Once their numbers were ported over and they were able to experience the mobile app, they felt it was not a good solution for their business. Their reasoning was:
Calls/texts are intermittent (we have asked for examples of this to help troubleshoot to see if this is an actual programming error or if it is the nature of the mobile app - the office is unwilling to troubleshoot/provide examples & data. All testing and auditing on our end has shown call routing and texting numbers to be set up as expected.
"It's clear this system was designed for medical offices, and it's not really a good fit for sales"
All other reasoning pointed to frustration with issues they experienced, which are now resolved and outlined below
Events that escalated their frustration were few and quickly resolved, but included:
After porting, calls were going straight to voicemail as call groups did not include any devices. They were instructed (at the beginning of the process) to either add the necessary user's mobile apps to the desired call groups before porting, or to send us a list of which users should be included so we could set this up for them, but neither option occurred until they reached out to let me know they weren't receiving calls.
After porting, instruction sets were not updated with the labels for 6 of their numbers that had ported. This was quickly resolved once the error was found due to the report of calls going to the wrong location.
They reported that texts were going to "all users" or to the wrong location, or being sent with the wrong number/receiving messages from random numbers, but they were unable to provide specific examples of this. I tested every location that had a ported number set up, and all outbound texts were successful (with the right number) and inbound texts were successfully received to the proper account.
Items we have identified on our end that may have helped the transition go more smoothly:
Porting occurred on the main Weave account as all of their numbers were on the same account with RingCentral, which allowed more opportunity for errors in provision. The numbers had to be manually moved to the proper location on each port day, which is how the instruction sets were missed for a few lines.
We should have followed up on the call groups to confirm devices were included before the port day - including mobile users having logged into the app to create their SIP profile.

Office is concerned about connecting their phones, which cased a long delay on the account. They don't have ethernet ports, but are not happy that we don't recommend wifi. They requested to cancel after feeling like we didn't recommend or support wifi as he doesn't want to implement wall ports to his office. Offered credits, AE and OB were both unable to save.
